Locality: Susquehanna WTP--Washington Boro (restricted access, view from outside fence only)
Observation Details: Continuing rarity, presumably the same individual that wintered here last year. Originally, found on a CBC on 12/31/2022; first spotted by Joe Melony and reported by Jonathan Heller. I went and saw the bird on January 2, a lifer then. Apparently, the bird continued for a long time, last being seen sometime around the end of March. Now, on 10/23/2023, the bird was spotted at the nearby Washington Boro Park by Stanley C. Stahl, who then recorded it the following day back at the water treatment plant. From what I've observed, the bird has been a lot more hit or miss than it was last winter. Since I was in the area, I decided I'd stop by for a couple minutes to hopefully get a glimpse of the bird flycatching around the hypochlorite tanks as it did last winter.  What I didn't expect was to pull up to the fence, look down at my phone to record my start time, then look back up to see the phoebe bound through the air and land directly in front of my car. Got to watch it very close up for a minute or so, but didn't get pictures because if I'd moved I would've scared it. But how amazing to see this western bird right in front of me in Pennsylvania!  Eventually it flew off but I decided to position myself better and wait for another opportunity for pictures this time. It took almost two hours, the bird mostly flying around the tanks and the roof of the nearby building, and several times frustratingly farther down the fence, but finally it flew back in to the fence where I was waiting and posed gorgeously. So happy to get a picture I'm happy with of this rare species!!

Observation Details: ***Rare, 3rd Piedmont record and westernmost NC record, obviously a county 1st and #225 for me in Union County.  First spotted flying directly away from my car. I figured the bird was a female bluebird (based on the silvery-gray) and realized it was a phoebe when it perched on a fencepost. Quickly noticed the salmon-pink belly and promptly freaked out. It flew off for a few nerve-wracking minutes, but returned and gave absolutely incredible views.   Medium-sized flycatcher with dark gray head, silvery mantle and wings, salmon belly and undertail, and noticeable solid black tail. More elongated than Eastern Phoebe, and slightly larger (had a few direct comparisons as the two species would sometimes squabble). The bird would perch prominently and sally out after bugs, often flying high into the air to pursuit. It occasionally wagged its tail, but not as frequently as Eastern Phoebe and in a much stiffer, pipit-like way. Sometimes landed in the road after bugs.   Bird mostly preferred the hayfield on the right (if facing the dead end) of the road, perching mostly on the fence but sometimes in the pecan trees. Please note that the road is a state road, so public property, but there are houses and farms nearby. This location has been excellent for rarities, so please stick to the road and avoid annoying the locals!

I was parked in early morning with my camera, on the dike road of Atkinson Lake, at the Schell-Osage CA.  The bird landed about thirty meters away, on a small sprout, then briefly spread its tail.  It sat immobile for less than a minute then left.  This was at 7:33, shortly after sunrise--just as the clouds began to roll in.  The temperature was about 45 degrees with a moderate southerly wind.. I usually visit Schell-Osage several times a week and this is the first and only Say's Phoebe I have ever seen there.  I lived in New Mexico for several decades and often saw them there.

**RARE | found previous day by Dave Fensore birding with his daughter. Continuing in the fields along the west side of Shaker Road, favoring the perimeter fences for perching while hunting aerial insects. Often working the temporary(!) electric fence (for sheep) close to the road or the permanent fence corner sticking into the field in the northwest. Did disappear for ~30 minutes during my 2hr observation.   Typical Sayornis structure (longer primaries than EAPH) and behavior but showing pale yellow-salmon underneath (not as rosy as others I've seen). Same pale yellow-pinkish shown on underwing coverts in flight and while preening. Ashy-gray on chest, back, and head except for darker masked appearance. Dark black tail obvious at a distance and when flared in flight; often gave it a thicker-tailed looked when perched. All bare parts dark.   Apparently the 16th record for Maine - only four [recent] records have been reviewed by ME-BRC so far. Vickery lists "at least 14 documented records, all but one coastal, and eight coming from Monhegan Island and adjoining Manana Island" but omits a 9th Monhegan record from 14-21 Sep 1992 (AB v47: 66). Of those, this is the second record for Cumberland County but currently the first submitted to eBird.

Locality: Quabbin Reservoir--Winsor Dam and Park Headquarters
Observation Details: I observed the bird for most of two hours between 9:15 am and 11:15. (I also saw it between 11:15 and 12:15, but less reliably.)  I had read only a few of the recent postings about it, and I wasn't prepared for how widely it ranged.  As I arrived it was pointed out to me (by a friendly birder: thank you!) as it perched at the top of the roof ladder at the back of the building that houses both the State Police and the park's Visitor Center and Headquarters.  The back of the building is where the bird seemed to spend most of its time, either on the lookout for prey, sallying out to catch it, or preening.  It is a very showy or dramatic hunter, spreading its wings wide and tumbling down and swooping up.  Sometimes it returned to its perch after a sally; sometimes it didn't.  It was visible from both the public parking lot side of the building (where the lighting was less than ideal for photography) and the side farther from the lot (where the lighting was better), but it spent more time on the side of the building near the parking lot.  It perched on the corners of chimneys, on a tall pole, on the ladder I've already mentioned, and on a fire escape, as well as on roof ridges, roof edges, and at the apex of dormer windows.  At one point I followed the bird as it rose above the building and headed towards the dam.  It perched at the very top of a tall conifer near the entrance to the dam.  At that point I lost it, but I found it again on a bush in the rain garden (to the left of the path or road from the building to the dam).  It then flew back towards the building. Then I saw it briefly in a tall tree on the reservoir side of the parking lot and on one of the signs advertising the pollinator meadow.  Still later I saw it near the reservoir across the entry road from the parking lot, in an area that bluebirds seem to favor.  It perched on the top of a lamppost and went to the ground.  It also perched on small trees close to the road.  At one point it flew close to the lattice fence between the road and the reservoir (where bluebirds sometimes perched) but didn't land on it, despite acting at several points as if it was about to do so.  I think the bird's lines are longer than an Eastern Phoebe's; it gives a more elegant or stretched out impression.  The bird generally (always?) flirted its tail several times upon landing, sometimes flaring its tail feathers.  In long flights it looked as if it was merely "flicking" its wings several times (as opposed to taking deep strokes) between glides.  At one point (captured I believe in one of the photos I've posted) it called: a distinctly two-parted, descending _pee-yeeer_.

Locality: BCVA-- Zion Church x Smith Town Rd.
Observation Details: ***Rare, 3rd Piedmont record and westernmost NC record, obviously a county 1st and #225 for me in Union County.  First spotted flying directly away from my car. I figured the bird was a female bluebird (based on the silvery-gray) and realized it was a phoebe when it perched on a fencepost. Quickly noticed the salmon-pink belly and promptly freaked out. It flew off for a few nerve-wracking minutes, but returned and gave absolutely incredible views.   Medium-sized flycatcher with dark gray head, silvery mantle and wings, salmon belly and undertail, and noticeable solid black tail. More elongated than Eastern Phoebe, and slightly larger (had a few direct comparisons as the two species would sometimes squabble). The bird would perch prominently and sally out after bugs, often flying high into the air to pursuit. It occasionally wagged its tail, but not as frequently as Eastern Phoebe and in a much stiffer, pipit-like way. Sometimes landed in the road after bugs.   Bird mostly preferred the hayfield on the right (if facing the dead end) of the road, perching mostly on the fence but sometimes in the pecan trees. Please note that the road is a state road, so public property, but there are houses and farms nearby. This location has been excellent for rarities, so please stick to the road and avoid annoying the locals!

Locality: Quabbin Reservoir--Winsor Dam and Park Headquarters
Observation Details: I observed the bird for most of two hours between 9:15 am and 11:15. (I also saw it between 11:15 and 12:15, but less reliably.)  I had read only a few of the recent postings about it, and I wasn't prepared for how widely it ranged.  As I arrived it was pointed out to me (by a friendly birder: thank you!) as it perched at the top of the roof ladder at the back of the building that houses both the State Police and the park's Visitor Center and Headquarters.  The back of the building is where the bird seemed to spend most of its time, either on the lookout for prey, sallying out to catch it, or preening.  It is a very showy or dramatic hunter, spreading its wings wide and tumbling down and swooping up.  Sometimes it returned to its perch after a sally; sometimes it didn't.  It was visible from both the public parking lot side of the building (where the lighting was less than ideal for photography) and the side farther from the lot (where the lighting was better), but it spent more time on the side of the building near the parking lot.  It perched on the corners of chimneys, on a tall pole, on the ladder I've already mentioned, and on a fire escape, as well as on roof ridges, roof edges, and at the apex of dormer windows.  At one point I followed the bird as it rose above the building and headed towards the dam.  It perched at the very top of a tall conifer near the entrance to the dam.  At that point I lost it, but I found it again on a bush in the rain garden (to the left of the path or road from the building to the dam).  It then flew back towards the building. Then I saw it briefly in a tall tree on the reservoir side of the parking lot and on one of the signs advertising the pollinator meadow.  Still later I saw it near the reservoir across the entry road from the parking lot, in an area that bluebirds seem to favor.  It perched on the top of a lamppost and went to the ground.  It also perched on small trees close to the road.  At one point it flew close to the lattice fence between the road and the reservoir (where bluebirds sometimes perched) but didn't land on it, despite acting at several points as if it was about to do so.  I think the bird's lines are longer than an Eastern Phoebe's; it gives a more elegant or stretched out impression.  The bird generally (always?) flirted its tail several times upon landing, sometimes flaring its tail feathers.  In long flights it looked as if it was merely "flicking" its wings several times (as opposed to taking deep strokes) between glides.  At one point (captured I believe in one of the photos I've posted) it called: a distinctly two-parted, descending _pee-yeeer_.

Continuing juvenile bird found yesterday by Ken and Sue Feustel. Slightly larger than EAPH with peachy coloring from belly to vent area and black tail. Extremely territorial- aggressively chasing away EAPHs and continually catching insects. An absolute pleasure to view. Photos.

**RARE | found previous day by Dave Fensore birding with his daughter. Continuing in the fields along the west side of Shaker Road, favoring the perimeter fences for perching while hunting aerial insects. Often working the temporary(!) electric fence (for sheep) close to the road or the permanent fence corner sticking into the field in the northwest. Did disappear for ~30 minutes during my 2hr observation.   Typical Sayornis structure (longer primaries than EAPH) and behavior but showing pale yellow-salmon underneath (not as rosy as others I've seen). Same pale yellow-pinkish shown on underwing coverts in flight and while preening. Ashy-gray on chest, back, and head except for darker masked appearance. Dark black tail obvious at a distance and when flared in flight; often gave it a thicker-tailed looked when perched. All bare parts dark.   Apparently the 16th record for Maine - only four [recent] records have been reviewed by ME-BRC so far. Vickery lists "at least 14 documented records, all but one coastal, and eight coming from Monhegan Island and adjoining Manana Island" but omits a 9th Monhegan record from 14-21 Sep 1992 (AB v47: 66). Of those, this is the second record for Cumberland County but currently the first submitted to eBird.

Continuing bird found by Lyle.  Stayed low on fence most of the time. Calling frequently a plaintive rising then slowly falling quweeeee somewhat similar in tone to Pacific golden plover. 1st cycle bird finished with a partial preformative molt recently. Primary coverts and most secondaries were juvenile feathers and were contrasting brown with new formative feathers.  Primaries appeared new. Two ages of greater coverts apparent contrasting close to center. 4th tertiary possibly old but hard to determine from my photos. Inner 3 replaced.  Retrices hard to age but several appeared worn on the tips suggesting juvenile feathers.  Missing primary on left wing (P3 told from some flight shots from Edwin) leaving noticeable gap. No molt though. Overall a larger grayish bird than EAPH. Smaller petite bill. Crested head and large wide black tail most noticeable in flight. Distinctive tail twitching. Very pale and transculesent primaries

I spotted what I was quite sure was a Say's Phoebe at the far NE edge of the sink while scoping from the south parking lot. Excitedly, I made the slogging trek across the recently burned landscape to the far NE side to confirm my ID. As I made my way to the bird, I lost sight of it. I continued at a slower pace dejected by the apparently MIA, not yet well-documented find. I arrived at the NE corner to find the bird had relocated back to the western edge where I just come from. I worked my way back in that direction where I obtained the first acceptable doc shots. Shortly thereafter the bird made its way back to the NE corner. Exasperated I contemplated the pros/cons of a return trek to ground zero Say's. I went for it frozen wet toes and all. The chase became frustratingly more uncomfortable as my toes were colder and wind was gusting during this mid-April return to winter. Peter came out to join me with fresh batteries for my camera. We enjoyed closer looks at the NE end before the bird worked its way back to the western edge. It sallied from its stubble perches to the ground where it enjoyed the bounty of insects present on the charred landscape. After making our way back to the western edge others joined us to watch the phoebe continue to feed. We heard the bird departed west toward the quarry shortly after we left the area. Description: flycatcher bobbing tail. Brownish gray upper parts with weak double wing bars. Blended dark area bill through eye, darker than rest of head. Muted salmon pink lower breast, dusky upper breast. Lacking streaks of a female VEFL. Distinct black tail. Dark eye. Photos.
Photos. May have been 2 different birds.

Observation Details: Spent about 2 hours at Black rock Sanctuary  in overcast but mild (55 degrees) weather. I was on the second loop around when I came up to the meadow area which abuts the car park, when at about 100 feet away I heard calling and viewed what appeared as a 6-7 inch flycatcher or phoebe. It was staying in the low trees ( appx 4 feet off the ground) on perch and then dipping down, hovering about 2 feet off of the ground for 5-10 seconds at a time , looking for insects. I observed the behavior for over 20 minutes until the bird flew off to the first adjoining private property . Fortunately I was able to get some wonderful photographs before he/she flew off!

Observation Details: I saw a Phoebe-like bird perching on a piece of garden furniture at the front edge of large open area or fields about half a mile ESE of the hamlet of Churchtown in Columbia County.  It looked a little different, but was pumping it’s tail and I just marked it down as a fall plumage Eastern Phoebe. When I looked through binoculars, though, I saw it had an all gray head, gray back and grayish throat, dark tail, and was clearly reddish/brown on the lower belly.  I came back about half an hour later with a camera and include the attached photo.  Apologies for the late post, but it took a while to get the image uploaded, and also to have professional ornithologist colleagues weigh in!

Observation Details: RARE, found by Al Schenck. First seen just before 8:00 feeding actively around the red silos and barn near the parking lot (41.8439417, -71.5413229). Very young bird, still with noticeable yellow at the gape, and with fairly prominent pale wingbars. Relatively dull below but distinctive salmon-ish color to underparts, and uniformly dusky head and back, becoming slightly paler on the breast. Solid black ‘censorship bar’ of a tail, often dipped/wagged. Noticeably larger than EAPH, and slightly different foraging style, with much more prolonged hovering. Seemed to be moving in ever-increasing circles around the barn and house by the parking lot, eventually disappearing across the street towards Dame Farm.

Observation Details: Circumstances of finding the bird (if applicable): While conducting the WPBO waterbird count, I noticed a bird flycatching from a dead Jack Pine NW from the Waterbird Shack. When I got the bird in my spotting scope, I immediately identified it as a Say’s Phoebe.  Habitat: Perching on Jack Pine’s in an open area. Vocalization(s): None  Behavior: Perched and flycatching in flight.  Description – This bird was similar in size and structure to Eastern Phoebe (one of which was seen after this bird had left). This bird had a gray head and breast, all black bill, pale rufous belly and undertail coverts, black tail and pale wingbars.

Rare, but one of the more frequently occurring western species on LI in Fall. Second record for Caumsett State Park. Bird observed flycatching all around Caumsett's grassy overflow parking area lying north of the old office and bathroom buildings. An extremely aggressive individual, observed chasing Eastern Phoebes, Savannah Sparrows and Eastern Bluebirds with gusto. Considerably larger than EAPH, bird appeared dark above and mottled below, with peach-colored lower breast and undertail coverts. Tail was black. No vocalizations heard. Photos to follow.

Observation Details: **RARE -- found by Dave Fensore yesterday and first seen this morning by D. Lovitch, along with D. Fensore, P. Moynahan, and M. Gilbert.   Flycatching from small white electric fence in cattle/sheep pasture by the Shaker Village. Moved up and down the length of the fence, and occasionally disappeared for minutes at a time before reappearing somewhere else. Also moved to the opposite side of the field and perched on wooden fence corner/bluebird boxes with EAPH. Flushed by AMKE from electric fence once.  Typical Sayornis shape and behavior, but with a noticeably more elongated body than an Eastern Phoebe. Head peaked towards rear, and bill slightly longer and noticeably thinner. Dusty gray-brown on back and head, notched all-black tail, pale salmon-orange belly, vent, and undertail coverts, pale wingbars and pale-edged tertials. Frequently hovered for short periods above the ground, and bobbed and flipped its tail.

Observation Details: Continuing bird found by Lyle.  Stayed low on fence most of the time. Calling frequently a plaintive rising then slowly falling quweeeee somewhat similar in tone to Pacific golden plover. 1st cycle bird finished with a partial preformative molt recently. Primary coverts and most secondaries were juvenile feathers and were contrasting brown with new formative feathers.  Primaries appeared new. Two ages of greater coverts apparent contrasting close to center. 4th tertiary possibly old but hard to determine from my photos. Inner 3 replaced.  Retrices hard to age but several appeared worn on the tips suggesting juvenile feathers.  Missing primary on left wing (P3 told from some flight shots from Edwin) leaving noticeable gap. No molt though. Overall a larger grayish bird than EAPH. Smaller petite bill. Crested head and large wide black tail most noticeable in flight. Distinctive tail twitching. Very pale and transculesent primaries

**RARE -- found by Dave Fensore yesterday and first seen this morning by D. Lovitch, along with D. Fensore, P. Moynahan, and M. Gilbert.   Flycatching from small white electric fence in cattle/sheep pasture by the Shaker Village. Moved up and down the length of the fence, and occasionally disappeared for minutes at a time before reappearing somewhere else. Also moved to the opposite side of the field and perched on wooden fence corner/bluebird boxes with EAPH. Flushed by AMKE from electric fence once.  Typical Sayornis shape and behavior, but with a noticeably more elongated body than an Eastern Phoebe. Head peaked towards rear, and bill slightly longer and noticeably thinner. Dusty gray-brown on back and head, notched all-black tail, pale salmon-orange belly, vent, and undertail coverts, pale wingbars and pale-edged tertials. Frequently hovered for short periods above the ground, and bobbed and flipped its tail.

**RARE | found previous day by Dave Fensore birding with his daughter. Continuing in the fields along the west side of Shaker Road, favoring the perimeter fences for perching while hunting aerial insects. Often working the temporary(!) electric fence (for sheep) close to the road or the permanent fence corner sticking into the field in the northwest. Did disappear for ~30 minutes during my 2hr observation.   Typical Sayornis structure (longer primaries than EAPH) and behavior but showing pale yellow-salmon underneath (not as rosy as others I've seen). Same pale yellow-pinkish shown on underwing coverts in flight and while preening. Ashy-gray on chest, back, and head except for darker masked appearance. Dark black tail obvious at a distance and when flared in flight; often gave it a thicker-tailed looked when perched. All bare parts dark.   Apparently the 16th record for Maine - only four [recent] records have been reviewed by ME-BRC so far. Vickery lists "at least 14 documented records, all but one coastal, and eight coming from Monhegan Island and adjoining Manana Island" but omits a 9th Monhegan record from 14-21 Sep 1992 (AB v47: 66). Of those, this is the second record for Cumberland County but currently the first submitted to eBird.

Locality: Quabbin Reservoir--Winsor Dam and Park Headquarters
Observation Details: I observed the bird for most of two hours between 9:15 am and 11:15. (I also saw it between 11:15 and 12:15, but less reliably.)  I had read only a few of the recent postings about it, and I wasn't prepared for how widely it ranged.  As I arrived it was pointed out to me (by a friendly birder: thank you!) as it perched at the top of the roof ladder at the back of the building that houses both the State Police and the park's Visitor Center and Headquarters.  The back of the building is where the bird seemed to spend most of its time, either on the lookout for prey, sallying out to catch it, or preening.  It is a very showy or dramatic hunter, spreading its wings wide and tumbling down and swooping up.  Sometimes it returned to its perch after a sally; sometimes it didn't.  It was visible from both the public parking lot side of the building (where the lighting was less than ideal for photography) and the side farther from the lot (where the lighting was better), but it spent more time on the side of the building near the parking lot.  It perched on the corners of chimneys, on a tall pole, on the ladder I've already mentioned, and on a fire escape, as well as on roof ridges, roof edges, and at the apex of dormer windows.  At one point I followed the bird as it rose above the building and headed towards the dam.  It perched at the very top of a tall conifer near the entrance to the dam.  At that point I lost it, but I found it again on a bush in the rain garden (to the left of the path or road from the building to the dam).  It then flew back towards the building. Then I saw it briefly in a tall tree on the reservoir side of the parking lot and on one of the signs advertising the pollinator meadow.  Still later I saw it near the reservoir across the entry road from the parking lot, in an area that bluebirds seem to favor.  It perched on the top of a lamppost and went to the ground.  It also perched on small trees close to the road.  At one point it flew close to the lattice fence between the road and the reservoir (where bluebirds sometimes perched) but didn't land on it, despite acting at several points as if it was about to do so.  I think the bird's lines are longer than an Eastern Phoebe's; it gives a more elegant or stretched out impression.  The bird generally (always?) flirted its tail several times upon landing, sometimes flaring its tail feathers.  In long flights it looked as if it was merely "flicking" its wings several times (as opposed to taking deep strokes) between glides.  At one point (captured I believe in one of the photos I've posted) it called: a distinctly two-parted, descending _pee-yeeer_.

Observation Details: Continuing bird found by Jody Wells earlier this morning and periodically reported by others throughout the day until Nathan Earley very kindly stuck on the bird for around an hour to help me see it after driving like a madman down from Nanoose after an IBA Brant Survey there.  Ochre-bellied gray-backed flycatcher actively fly catching off the barb wire airport perimeter fence being periodically harassed by Red-winged Blackbirds and a North Shrike. Super obliging and allowed for unparalleled views + photos. Didn’t vocalize but did catch a caterpillar, so I guess you can’t have it all.  #165 for the Vancouver Island Big Year and feeling as grateful as ever to the birding community!

Observation Details: Found by Larry Pace yesterday afternoon. Sayornis-type flycatcher with gray back and breast and salmon-colored belly. This bird also showed a contrastingly black tail, which we noticed several times as it preened and sallied. We observed that it heavily favored power lines, but it did occasionally put down in the brush along the stream. We also noticed that it had a somewhat large range, moving from the stream, down the power line about a 1/4 mile north of the road, and across the road on the south side (useful to know if the bird isn’t immediately visible). Hopefully this fellow stays put for awhile…it seemed comfortable but did occasionally get harassed by a nearby shrike. My pin for this checklist should be pretty precise for others chasing. Photos.

Continuing bird found by the Feustels on Thursday. Foraging actively from elevated perches along the split rail fence, wooden fence segments, and forest edge north of the parking lot. Aggressively chased Eastern Phoebes, and frequently hovered in place low over the ground before pouncing on insect prey. Hatch year bird, grayish overall with a washed-out, faint salmon wash on the lower belly and vent. Head slightly duskier than the rest of the body, tail pitch black. Faint pale edges on the upperwing coverts formed indistinct wingbars. A bit more slender and elegantly-proportioned than an Eastern, definitely a tail-bobber

Observation Details: **RARE | this bird was present in this private yard from 6-9 September 2016 found by Joe Mallory. He contacted Maine Audubon and allowed me to visit and document (photograph) the bird. The Mallorys did not want additional visitors and were worried about disturbing the bird but allow public access for a couple hours on the 8th. JM submitted a thorough report to the ME-BRC.  This dusky-peachy breasted flycatcher with a long black tail was perched on the side of the Mallory's house for the majority of my visit. They said it was very active in the prior evening and that morning but did very little foraging during this time and actually would close its eyes for a short time (never falling asleep) while watching it from a distance. I approached twice for photos and it never reacted to my presence.

Relocated here after it flushed west from the end of Schneider Mill Court.  From rare bird report for MBRC:  "Originally perched on small dead shrubs at the end of Schneider Mill Court, then got flushed by a Cooper’s Hawk and flew west. It was then refound at Kaufman Sports Complex where it was observed hawking from the tops of chain link fences for several hours; it would fly quite high or for quite long distances before returning to its original perch or landing 20-30 feet farther down the fence. Constantly and energetically bobbing its tail. Occasionally took high flight and landed on a fence far away. It was heard vocalizing sporadically, especially right after I relocated it at the sports complex. At the sports complex it twice perched incidentally in the same area as two Eastern Phoebes, although it did not seem to be directly associating with them. At about 12:50 the three observers present (me, Alec Olivier, and Jeff Knoop) were all very briefly preoccupied and somehow completely lost track of the bird—it vanished and was not seen again from then on." "Vocalized several times; call was a clear and rather rich descending whistle lasting less than one second. Sang twice; song was a similarly rich and clear “whip whoEEEeww”, quite fast with the last phrase going from low to high to low in pitch and descending at the end." "Even before getting binoculars on it, immediately knew it was a phoebe of some sort by gestalt. Slim flycatcher with medium-length slightly-notched tail, peaked head, and thin bill. Noticeably larger than Eastern Phoebes nearby, and appeared slightly larger than a nearby Eastern Bluebird. Bill dark and fairly short with a narrow but rounded (not at all hooked) tip. Eyes appeared all dark. Legs and feet dark gray. Overall a grayish bird; back, crown, breast, and much of face all medium gray. Auriculars and especially the lores a darker gray; throat distinctly paler gray but not particularly contrasting with the rest of the bird. Wings and tail dark gray. Gray upper breast blended into a wonderful peachy cinnamon color on the rest of the underparts. This color intensified lower down on the underparts and was brightest in the undertail coverts and especially the vent."

Observation Details: Spent about 2 hours at Black rock Sanctuary  in overcast but mild (55 degrees) weather. I was on the second loop around when I came up to the meadow area which abuts the car park, when at about 100 feet away I heard calling and viewed what appeared as a 6-7 inch flycatcher or phoebe. It was staying in the low trees ( appx 4 feet off the ground) on perch and then dipping down, hovering about 2 feet off of the ground for 5-10 seconds at a time , looking for insects. I observed the behavior for over 20 minutes until the bird flew off to the first adjoining private property . Fortunately I was able to get some wonderful photographs before he/she flew off!

Observation Details: Found by Larry Pace yesterday afternoon. Sayornis-type flycatcher with gray back and breast and salmon-colored belly. This bird also showed a contrastingly black tail, which we noticed several times as it preened and sallied. We observed that it heavily favored power lines, but it did occasionally put down in the brush along the stream. We also noticed that it had a somewhat large range, moving from the stream, down the power line about a 1/4 mile north of the road, and across the road on the south side (useful to know if the bird isn’t immediately visible). Hopefully this fellow stays put for awhile…it seemed comfortable but did occasionally get harassed by a nearby shrike. My pin for this checklist should be pretty precise for others chasing. Photos.

Appeared slightly heavier than Eastern Phoebe but with similar behavior; tail pumping and foraging from low prominent perches. Ph.

On 10-25-2015, at Max A. Mandel Municipal Golf Course in Laredo, Texas, I observed and photographed a Say's Phoebe, a bird that is rare in Webb County, Texas, according to eBird data. According to the TOS Handbook of Texas Birds (2nd ed., 2014), Say's Phoebe "is a common to uncommon resident in the Trans-Pecos and east to the western edge of the Edwards Plateau. Say's Phoebes are rare and local summer residents on the High Plains of the western Panhandle south through the South Plains to the northwestern edge of the Edwards Plateau. They are also rare to very rare migrants and winter visitors through the Rolling Plains and uncommon during these seasons in the South Texas Brush Country. This species is a rare, but regular winter visitor east to the central coast and the Blackland Prairies region from north-central Texas south to Bastrop County. They are casual visitors to the eastern quarter of the state, mostly in fall and winter." I observed the Say's Phoebe in the photograph at 12:32 pm. I observed and photographed a second Say's Phoebe at 2:22 pm (possibly the same bird) at the eastern end of the golf course, sitting in a plowed field.

The attached photos are not real sharp, given the distance of the shots, but they clearly support the identification of the Say's Phoebe as a midsized flycatcher with contrasty black tail, grayish breast, and cinnamon or orange-buff belly.
